				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Argentina Ordered to Resume Talks With Hedge Fund</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Alexandra Stevenson			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-08-01T18:43:31+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">August 1, 2014 2:43 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">August 1, 2014 2:43 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina4/dbpix-argentina4-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina4/dbpix-argentina4-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina4/dbpix-argentina4-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003034676" width="592" height="395" alt="The Casa Rosada Presidential Palace in the financial district of Buenos Aires on Friday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The Casa Rosada Presidential Palace in the financial district of Buenos Aires on Friday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Marcos Brindicci/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/08/01/u-s-judge-rejects-argentinas-appeal-for-new-mediator/" data-title="Argentina Ordered to Resume Talks With Hedge Fund" data-description="A federal judge said talks would have to continue with a group of hedge funds that hold Argentina&#039;s bonds. Otherwise, the judge said: &quot;What is to happen? Another 10 years of irresolution?â ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/31/argentina-is-in-default-and-also-maybe-in-denial/">Argentina Is in Default, And Also Maybe in Denial (July 31, 2014)</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A lawyer for Argentina told a federal judge on Friday that the nation had lost faith in the mediator appointed to work with a group of <a title="Argentina Is in Default, And Also Maybe in Denial (July 31, 2014)" href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/31/argentina-is-in-default-and-also-maybe-in-denial/">hedge funds thatÂ  hold the country&#8217;s bonds</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The lawyer, Jonathan Blackman, pointed to a statement issued by the mediator, Daniel Pollack, on Wednesday that said Argentina was in &#8220;imminent default.&#8221; That statement, Mr. Blackman said, was âharmful and prejudicial,â and he asked that Mr.<br />
Pollack be replaced</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the judge, Thomas P. Griesa of Federal District Court in Manhattan, rejected the request and said talks would have to continue. But whether Judge Griesa and Argentina&#8217;s intentions are aligned is another matter.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Wednesday, Argentina slipped into its second default in 13 years after missing a regular bond payment. The news sent Argentinaâs bonds and stocks into turmoil on Thursday and Friday.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina3/dbpix-argentina3-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina3/dbpix-argentina3-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina3/dbpix-argentina3-blog480.jpg" id="100000003034675" width="480" height="320" alt="Daniel Pollack, a mediator appointed to work with hedge funds who hold Argentinaâs bonds."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Daniel Pollack, a mediator appointed to work with hedge funds who hold Argentinaâs bonds.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Carlo Allegri/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For years, Argentina has been battling with a group of hedge funds that hold bonds that it defaulted on in 2001. The country eventually exchanged most of its bonds for discounted ones, but these investors refused to participate in the exchange, earning them the title of holdouts. In 2012, the battle reached a pitch when Judge Griesa ruled that Argentina could not continue to pay exchange bondholders without also paying the holdouts.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This week, last-minute mediated talks between the holdouts and a delegation of Argentine officials that included Axel Kicillof, the economy minister, broke down, and Argentina passed a deadline to make a payment to its exchange bondholders. Ratings agencies downgraded its debt in response.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Friday, Mr. Blackman said Mr. Pollackâs statement had caused Argentina âdeep concern.â He said the country had lost trust in the process mediated by Mr. Pollack.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina2/dbpix-argentina2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina2/dbpix-argentina2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina2/dbpix-argentina2-blog480.jpg" id="100000003034500" width="480" height="320" alt="Jonathan Blackman, Carmine Boccuzzi and Michael Brennan, lawyers for Argentina."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Jonathan Blackman, Carmine Boccuzzi and Michael Brennan, lawyers for Argentina.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Carlo Allegri/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Judge Griesa, who appointed Mr. Pollack to help mediate the last-ditch talks, responded that something had to be said to the public after talks broke down and Argentina missed its bond payment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt can hardly be said to be inaccurate,â he added.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Robert Cohen, a lawyer representing the holdouts, who are being led by Paul Singerâs hedge fund NML Capital, said Mr. Pollackâs statement âmerely reflected the facts.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe fact is, and the world knows, that they are in default,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Judge Griesa, who at times revealed his frustration with what he called Argentinaâs âlawlessâ actions, emphasized the importance of continuing the mediated talks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt cannot be left hanging,&#8221; he said. &#8220;What is to happen? Another 10 years of irresolution?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In case his intentions were not clear, he added, âNo.â</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina5/dbpix-argentina5-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina5/dbpix-argentina5-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/02/business/dbpix-argentina5/dbpix-argentina5-blog480.jpg" id="100000003034677" width="480" height="320" alt="President Cristina FernÃ¡ndez de Kirchner of Argentina."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">President Cristina FernÃ¡ndez de Kirchner of Argentina.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Marcos Brindicci/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
